SIMPLE: heed
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Heed
<hw>Heed</hw> <pr>(h⟦emac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Heeded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Heeding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>heden</ets>, AS.
<ets>h⟦emac⟧dan</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>h⟦omac⟧dian</ets>, D.
<ets>hoeden</ets>, Fries. <ets>hoda</ets>, OHG. <ets>huoten</ets>, G.
<ets>h⟦uum⟧ten</ets>, Dan. <ets>hytte</ets>. ⟦root⟧13. Cf.
<er>Hood</er>.]</ety> <def>To mind; to regard with care; to take notice
of; to attend to; to observe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With pleasure Argus the musician <qex>heeds</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To notice; regard; mind. See <er>Attend</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos></syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Heed
<hw>Heed</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To mind; to consider.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heed</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Heed
<hw>Heed</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Attention; notice;
observation; regard; -- often with <xex>give</xex> or
<xex>take</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With wanton <qex>heed</qex> and giddy cunning.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Amasa took no <qex>heed</qex> to the sword that was in Joab's
hand.</q> <rj><qau>2 Sam. xx. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Birds give more <qex>heed</qex> and mark words more than
beasts.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Careful consideration; obedient regard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Therefore we ought to give the more earnest <qex>heed</qex> to the
things which we have heard.</q> <rj><qau>Heb. ii. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A look or expression of heading.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He did it with a serious mind; a <qex>heed</qex>⟦br⟧
Was in his countenance.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heedful</ent>⟦br⟧
